english:
  title: Second Memorial
  author: Choe Chi-won
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I humbly submit that all things fear excess, and vessels brim with ruin—an ancient truth, a warning still. Should one forget restraint and covet honor alone, the tripod's legs will snap, and blades will cook in desperation.

    I have long pondered my fate: granted the favor of this enlightened age, I inherited the deeds of my forebears. North, I pacified the barbarian hordes; south, I subdued distant tribes; east, I received the surrender of bandits; west, I established citadels. Thus I raised my modest authority and extended my ambitions to the four directions. Yet when smoke and shadow gathered evil, when soldiers camped upon the plains, I proved myself unequal to the task of command. Though I held power over many, I lacked the wisdom for great strategy. I could not be first to voice righteousness, nor lead my troops with distinction—could not slay the leviathan in the marshes or chase the mad dog from the frontier.

    Then suddenly flames consumed the temples, dust alarmed the imperial carriage. Word came of the sovereign's journey, and talk turned to war. But each time I swore my soldiers to oath, orders arrived to halt. Thus my years dissolved in contradiction—advancing and retreating both gone awry. Like Hwa Won whose song of defense brought reproach, like Ja San whose counsel earned the realm's disdain, so fell I into disfavor. For three years suspicion has festered between factions; insects chorus their discord, oyster and crane trade their barbs. Slander coils upon the tongue, accusations cloud the sovereign's mind—I sought escape but found none, sought to flee but was bound.

    I trust in your wisdom, my lord—that you might illuminate my case as the great ministers of old, that you might untangle what seems knotted. Spare me the penalty of law; grant that I yet remain in service, washed clean by your judgment. Now must I steel my heart against ambition and devote myself entirely to the realm's service.

    Yet pine and bamboo, though they keep their color, cannot arrest what comes with age. The willow hastens toward autumn; my strength diminishes, my spirit flags. I wish to persevere, yet fear I shall fail.

    Now, mercifully, the capital is restored, and the imperial procession turns homeward. The strife of fierce spirits subsides; the age of war yields to peace. I, grown useless in this clear time, wish only to lay down my burdens. Not as one who seeks honored retirement, but as one who desires, like the ancient sage, to tend his garden in humble simplicity.

    I beseech you: select servants by wisdom, dismiss them with grace. Show mercy to this worn vessel and grant my petition. Though I cannot fully repay your kindness, release me from hollow office. I offer these clumsy words, hoping you will hear them. When urgency raises the voice, sorrow speaks clearly—but I fear my words grow thin and my meaning fails. I await your compassionate judgment.
  footnotes:
    - Choe Chi-won (846-910), a renowned Silla official and scholar, wrote this memorial during a period of political turbulence. The 'Second Memorial' appears to be a petition for retirement or relief from official duties.
    - References to historical examples (Hwa Won, Ja San) and sages (Qi Xi, Fan Li) are typical of Classical Chinese memorials, invoking precedent to support political arguments.
    - The imagery of broken tripods, mad dogs, and celestial omens reflects the political instability and court factional disputes of late Silla.
